SIMPLE: inclose
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inclose
<hw>In*close"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Inclosed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Inclosing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Enclose</er>,
and cf. <er>Include</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>enclose</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To surround; to shut in; to confine on all sides; to
include; to shut up; to encompass; <as>as, to <ex>inclose</ex> a fort or
an army with troops; to <ex>inclose</ex> a town with
walls.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How many evils have <qex>inclosed</qex> me round!</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put within a case, envelope, or the like; to fold
(a thing) within another or into the same parcel; <as>as, to
<ex>inclose</ex> a letter or a bank note</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>inclosed</qex> copies of the treaty.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To separate from common grounds by a fence; <as>as,
to <ex>inclose</ex> lands</as>.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To put into harness; to harness.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They went to coach and their horse <qex>inclose</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incloser</ent>⟦br⟧
